## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The **2019 Capital One breach** — which I have referenced multiple times in this project — is the canonical example of a requirements allocation failure in a cloud environment, and I want to revisit it one final time through today's specific lens.

The Capital One breach was caused by a misconfigured Web Application Firewall — a customer-managed control in MyCapital One's AWS environment. The WAF was Capital One's responsibility to configure correctly, not AWS's. Post-breach, there was no ambiguity about who was responsible — Capital One paid an $80 million penalty, not AWS.

But the breach investigation also revealed that an overprivileged IAM role — again, a customer-managed control — allowed the attacker who exploited the WAF misconfiguration to access far more data than a properly scoped role would have permitted. Two separate customer-managed controls failed: WAF configuration and IAM least privilege.

Both failures were in the hybrid and customer-specific categories of the shared responsibility model. AWS provided the WAF capability and the IAM capability — and both were functioning as designed. The configuration of those capabilities was Capital One's responsibility.

The Capital One case is the clearest possible illustration of why requirements allocation documentation matters. Not because it would have prevented the misconfiguration — documentation does not configure security controls. But because a clear requirements allocation matrix, reviewed regularly, creates the accountability structure that drives verification: "WAF configuration is our responsibility — has it been reviewed recently? IAM policies are our responsibility — when was the last least-privilege audit?" Those questions, asked regularly, are how misconfigurations get caught before they become breaches.

